# Zenith — copy to .env and fill in.
#
#   cp .env.example .env
#   cd deploy && docker compose --env-file ../.env up
#
# .env is gitignored. Everything in it is either a secret or a decision you
# only want to make once.

# ─── Required ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Signs every session token. There is no default, and Zenith refuses to start
# without it: a fallback would be the key signing every token in every
# deployment that forgot to change it.
#
#   openssl rand -base64 32
#
# Keep it stable. Changing it signs everyone out — which is also how you sign
# everyone out, if it ever leaks.
ZENITH_JWT_SECRET=

# ─── Your first account ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Created on first boot. An existing account is never overwritten, so leaving
# these set cannot reset your password on the next restart.
ZENITH_ADMIN_EMAIL=you@example.com

# At least 6 characters. Length is what resists an offline attack on a stolen
# hash, so that is the only rule.
ZENITH_ADMIN_PASSWORD=

# ─── Optional ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# The port Zenith is published on.
#ZENITH_PORT=8080

# How long a console session lasts.
#ZENITH_TOKEN_TTL=24h

# Country resolution. The compose files already handle this: a small `geoip`
# service downloads a current DB-IP Lite database to /data/country.mmdb before
# core starts, and core defaults to reading it there. You only need this
# variable to point somewhere else, or to set it empty to turn country lookup
# off.
#
# To supply a database yourself, any MaxMind-format country .mmdb will do:
#
#   DB-IP Lite (no account, easiest):
#     https://db-ip.com/db/download/ip-to-country-lite
#   MaxMind GeoLite2 (free, needs a signup and licence key):
#     https://dev.maxmind.com/geoip/geolite2-free-geolocation-data
#
# Both download gzipped, so gunzip first, then put the file on the data volume
# and point this at it:
#
#   docker cp country.mmdb <core-container>:/data/country.mmdb
#
# Mount it rather than copying it if your platform rebuilds the image, or it
# vanishes on the next deploy.
#
# Country is resolved when an event is recorded and the IP is then dropped, so
# adding this later cannot backfill: events already collected stay Unknown.
#ZENITH_GEOIP_DB=/data/country.mmdb

# How many SEO audits run at once. Each one is another set of live Chromium
# tabs, so this is the knob that bounds the worker's memory.
#ZENITH_AUDIT_CONCURRENCY=1

# ─── HTTPS (optional — the Caddy overlay) ────────────────────────────────────
#
# The hostname Caddy serves when you add deploy/docker-compose.caddy.yml, which
# puts Caddy in front of core and fetches a Let's Encrypt certificate on its
# own. Point this domain's A record at the server first, then:
#
#   docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.caddy.yml --env-file ../.env up -d
#
#ZENITH_DOMAIN=zenith.example.com

# ─── Not here ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The Resend API key and MAIL FROM are set in the console, under Settings, and
# stored in the database. They are configuration a developer changes, not
# deployment plumbing — and the key is never returned to a browser once saved.
#
# A site's keys are generated when you add the site. You never write them here.

# ─── Development only ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Lets core generate a throwaway signing secret so `go run ./cmd/core` works
# with no setup. It says so loudly on boot, and every restart signs everyone
# out. Never set this on a deployment.
#ZENITH_ENV=development
